00:14:34,480 --> 00:14:37,260
I spend all my time seeking out the truth,

241
00:14:37,440 --> 00:14:41,680
thinking about the truth, that I
have no time to practice rhetoric.

242
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:43,260
I'm not good with words.

243
00:14:44,640 --> 00:14:48,280
Also, I should not have to defend myself

244
00:14:49,080 --> 00:14:51,520
because you're all capable of reason.

245
00:14:51,720 --> 00:14:53,240
You're all capable of logic.

246
00:14:53,340 --> 00:14:55,400
Therefore, if you just think for yourself,

247
00:14:56,080 --> 00:14:57,900
you will realize I'm not guilty.

248
00:14:58,260 --> 00:15:01,840
I have absolutely nothing
to do with the 30 tyrants.

249
00:15:02,060 --> 00:15:05,860
I spent all my life trying to help Athens.

250
00:15:06,400 --> 00:15:09,460
Therefore, if you're stupid,
you will vote me guilty.

251
00:15:09,840 --> 00:15:12,620
If you're stupid, there's
nothing I can do about it, okay?

252
00:15:15,060 --> 00:15:17,760
Obviously, the jury was
insulted by his speech,

253
00:15:17,980 --> 00:15:20,260
and they voted out of 500 people,

254
00:15:21,660 --> 00:15:23,000
280 to 220,

255
00:15:24,580 --> 00:15:26,680
they voted that he is guilty, okay?

256
00:15:26,820 --> 00:15:29,880
They declared he was guilty
of these two charges.

257
00:15:30,320 --> 00:15:32,940
Now, as you can see, it's still
a pretty close vote, okay?

258
00:15:33,380 --> 00:15:36,220
I mean, Socrates was basically
being a jerk during the trial,

259
00:15:36,480 --> 00:15:39,580
and they still, they voted him guilty, but

260
00:15:39,580 --> 00:15:41,540
it was a pretty close trial, 280 to 220.

261
00:15:42,040 --> 00:15:45,820
Now, the second part of the trial
is, if you're found guilty,

262
00:15:48,400 --> 00:15:51,200
they have to figure out what
your punishment is, okay?

263
00:15:51,500 --> 00:15:55,760
So, the jury asked Socrates to
propose a punishment for his crimes.

264
00:15:56,240 --> 00:15:58,060
And then, what Socrates said was,

265
00:15:58,780 --> 00:16:02,460
you have found me guilty, and the
reason why you found me guilty is

266
00:16:02,460 --> 00:16:04,840
because I speak the truth.

267
00:16:05,240 --> 00:16:07,700
I am a gadfly, okay?

268
00:16:07,820 --> 00:16:10,520
Gadfly. I go around and

269
00:16:10,520 --> 00:16:14,060
I point out the nasty
truths of Athenian society.

270
00:16:14,760 --> 00:16:17,180
I put a mirror to your face, and

271
00:16:17,180 --> 00:16:20,120
I show you your warts, your
pimples, your ugliness.

272
00:16:21,160 --> 00:16:22,740
Therefore, you hate me.

273
00:16:23,520 --> 00:16:28,060
But, what I've been doing all
my life has been for the good

274
00:16:28,060 --> 00:16:29,620
and betterment of Athens.

275
00:16:29,900 --> 00:16:33,880
I'm a public servant. I am the
most selfless public servant,

276
00:16:34,120 --> 00:16:37,280
okay? Because I speak the truth,

277
00:16:37,500 --> 00:16:39,680
and by showing the truth,
I make you a better person.

278
00:16:40,520 --> 00:16:43,880
Therefore, I think a just
punishment would be a penchant.

279
00:16:44,180 --> 00:16:49,100
Okay? You guys should pay
me to retire in peace.

280
00:16:50,180 --> 00:16:51,380
But, you know what?

281
00:16:51,880 --> 00:16:54,360
I'm a generous and forgiving individual.

282
00:16:54,900 --> 00:16:57,640
Therefore, if you don't want to give
me a pension, I will understand.

283
00:16:58,020 --> 00:17:01,860
Therefore, I am willing
to pay a small fine, okay?

284
00:17:02,160 --> 00:17:04,100
I'll pay a fine, okay?

285
00:17:04,180 --> 00:17:05,560
And then, we're good.

286
00:17:06,500 --> 00:17:08,640
How about that? And again,

287
00:17:09,080 --> 00:17:11,820
the Athenian jurors
were pissed off, right?

288
00:17:12,180 --> 00:17:13,600
So, they voted to

289
00:17:14,180 --> 00:17:16,880
condemn him to death by
tricking him with a hemlock.

290
00:17:17,300 --> 00:17:19,100
Okay? They basically gave
him the death penalty.

291
00:17:20,480 --> 00:17:23,580
After they did so, they came to realize

292
00:17:23,580 --> 00:17:27,540
that they were perhaps
tricked by Socrates.

293
00:17:27,840 --> 00:17:30,540
Okay? Socrates was 70 years old.

294
00:17:31,480 --> 00:17:33,740
That's very old for back then, okay?

295
00:17:33,900 --> 00:17:38,160
70 years old was probably
the age limit back then.

296
00:17:38,360 --> 00:17:39,800
He really didn't have much to live for.

297
00:17:40,800 --> 00:17:45,660
And here was the opportunity for
Socrates to be a martyr for the truth,

298
00:17:45,800 --> 00:17:47,560
right? All his life,

299
00:17:47,600 --> 00:17:51,220
he's been trying to convince
people democracy does not work.

300
00:17:51,340 --> 00:17:56,040
Because people are incapable
of reasoning out the truth.

301
00:17:56,380 --> 00:18:00,240
And what this trial shows
us is he was correct.

302
00:18:01,080 --> 00:18:04,260
Right? Does that make
sense? So, in many ways,

303
00:18:04,480 --> 00:18:06,440
you can make the argument
that for Socrates,

304
00:18:06,900 --> 00:18:10,080
this trial was a type of performance art.

305
00:18:10,360 --> 00:18:13,880
Okay? He was a performance artist.

306
00:18:14,360 --> 00:18:18,360
Okay? And so, the people
of Athens realized

307
00:18:18,360 --> 00:18:21,960
that they were probably tricked.

308
00:18:22,120 --> 00:18:26,040
And they were trying to get out
of condemning Socrates to death.

309
00:18:26,260 --> 00:18:28,920
But Socrates insisted. And

310
00:18:28,920 --> 00:18:32,140
it came to a point where
Socrates was just left alone.

311
00:18:32,620 --> 00:18:34,640
And he had to demand
to be given a hemlock.

312
00:18:35,020 --> 00:18:37,260
And he had to administer
the hemlock by himself.

313
00:18:37,480 --> 00:18:38,980
And so, when he drank it, he died. Okay?

314
00:18:39,840 --> 00:18:43,920
Now, I'm going to give you a little
bit of a story. After his death,

315
00:18:44,100 --> 00:18:48,340
Socrates remained an extremely
controversial individual in Athens.

316
00:18:48,620 --> 00:18:51,880
And he had a student, Plato, who

317
00:18:51,880 --> 00:18:56,400
was maybe 28, 29 at the
time his mentor died.

318
00:18:56,620 --> 00:18:58,340
Okay? And he loved Socrates.

319
00:18:59,760 --> 00:19:04,020
And he committed the rest
of his life to restoring

320
00:19:04,020 --> 00:19:06,620
and redeeming the reputation of Socrates.

321
00:19:07,340 --> 00:19:10,340
So, when he was 40 years old,
he founded a school called

322
00:19:10,740 --> 00:19:13,540
The Academy. Okay?

323
00:19:14,340 --> 00:19:19,700
Which was inspired by the vision
of Socrates as a philosopher

324
00:19:19,700 --> 00:19:24,160
who sought the truth. In 375 BCE,

325
00:19:24,640 --> 00:19:26,980
he wrote a book called The Republic.

326
00:19:27,500 --> 00:19:31,480
And The Republic is the most
famous of Plato's work.

327
00:19:31,620 --> 00:19:34,460
It is arguably the greatest
work of Western philosophy.

328
00:19:34,800 --> 00:19:38,780
And many today consider The Republic
the greatest book ever written.

329
00:19:38,880 --> 00:19:40,720
Okay? There are people in this world
who have written a lot of great books.

330
00:19:40,720 --> 00:19:46,020
But they've never read The Republic. And it
forever transforms the way they see the world.

331
00:19:46,140 --> 00:19:49,500
Okay? It's a life transforming
event to read The Republic.

332
00:19:49,820 --> 00:19:51,780
And next semester, we will actually
read The Republic together.

333
00:19:52,060 --> 00:19:54,360
Okay? But let me give you a quick
introduction to The Republic.

334
00:19:54,980 --> 00:19:59,080
So, in The Republic, there's
a very famous metaphor.

335
00:20:00,720 --> 00:20:02,220
And it's called Allegory of the Cave.

336
00:20:07,020 --> 00:20:10,220
And this is really the most famous

337
00:20:11,860 --> 00:20:15,980
allegory or metaphor or analogy
in Western thought, okay?

338
00:20:16,180 --> 00:20:18,520
By fall. Nothing comes second to this.

339
00:20:18,900 --> 00:20:22,200
So before I start the
allegory of the cave,

340
00:20:22,420 --> 00:20:26,840
are there any questions so far about
what I've discussed? Anything unclear?

341
00:20:28,420 --> 00:20:34,400
Anything you would like to question or
doubt or argue with if I continue with the allegory of the cave?

342
00:20:37,800 --> 00:20:39,140
Okay? Clear so far?

343
00:20:39,260 --> 00:20:41,500
All right. So this is the allegory.

344
00:20:41,940 --> 00:20:46,020
Imagine a cave deep under the earth, okay?

345
00:20:46,100 --> 00:20:49,160
There's a cave. Now, in
this cave, at the back,

346
00:20:49,220 --> 00:20:51,840
there's a large fire that

347
00:20:51,840 --> 00:20:54,940
shines light into this cave, okay?

348
00:20:55,600 --> 00:20:58,300
There are these prisoners who

349
00:20:58,300 --> 00:21:00,860
are chained to the floor,

350
00:21:01,780 --> 00:21:04,940
and they're chained so that
they cannot move their necks.

351
00:21:05,060 --> 00:21:06,620
They can't move around, okay?

352
00:21:06,740 --> 00:21:10,760
They can't move. The only thing they can do is
steer at a wall, and they can't move around.

353
00:21:10,760 --> 00:21:12,820
That's the only thing they can do. Okay?

354
00:21:14,700 --> 00:21:18,580
Now, there are these people behind
them who are like puppeteers.

355
00:21:18,580 --> 00:21:23,780
They hold up cardboard
pictures of maybe rats

356
00:21:23,780 --> 00:21:25,860
and birds, okay?

357
00:21:26,140 --> 00:21:30,280
And the fire will project
these images onto the wall.

358
00:21:30,900 --> 00:21:34,080
And so these people, who
again cannot move around,

359
00:21:34,200 --> 00:21:37,060
and they can only see the wall in
front of them, they come to think that

360
00:21:37,060 --> 00:21:39,320
this wall is the truth.

361
00:21:39,360 --> 00:21:41,360
Okay? It's the only reality that exists.

362
00:21:41,920 --> 00:21:45,500
And they start naming things that

363
00:21:45,500 --> 00:21:47,000
they see, and that creates language.

364
00:21:48,040 --> 00:21:51,100
And they like to play
games and try to figure out

365
00:21:51,100 --> 00:21:54,820
who can create the best language, okay?

366
00:21:55,440 --> 00:21:59,020
And then they give awards to the people

367
00:21:59,020 --> 00:22:01,300
who create the best language
who are playwrights, right?

368
00:22:02,980 --> 00:22:06,560
Okay? So what Plato is saying is

369
00:22:06,560 --> 00:22:10,000
that we may honor art

370
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:14,060
and poetry and drama,
but they're all lies.

371
00:22:14,920 --> 00:22:17,740
Okay? Now,

372
00:22:17,740 --> 00:22:20,740
one day, for whatever reason,
we don't know why, but

373
00:22:20,740 --> 00:22:25,340
one man finds his chains are loosened.

374
00:22:25,540 --> 00:22:27,200
And he's able to get up.

375
00:22:27,760 --> 00:22:30,000
Okay? And he swims around, and

376
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:33,180
he sees a light coming from the top.

377
00:22:33,500 --> 00:22:36,900
So he's curious, and he
climbs all the way to the top,

378
00:22:36,980 --> 00:22:39,680
and he's now outside in the free world.

379
00:22:40,500 --> 00:22:43,300
Okay? And it's painful,

380
00:22:43,420 --> 00:22:47,900
because his eyes are not
trained to see the sunlight.

381
00:22:48,420 --> 00:22:50,460
Okay? So the sunlight,
it's like burning him.

382
00:22:50,620 --> 00:22:51,860
Okay? It's like burning him alive.

383
00:22:52,760 --> 00:22:56,040
And so at first, all he's
doing is staring at the ground.

384
00:22:56,260 --> 00:23:00,060
And so he's seeing reflections
in the pond, in the pool.

385
00:23:00,620 --> 00:23:02,700
But then he slowly acclimatizes himself.

386
00:23:02,860 --> 00:23:06,300
Two. And he starts to see
the world around him.

387
00:23:06,360 --> 00:23:07,760
And it's beautiful. Okay?

388
00:23:08,320 --> 00:23:12,000
But it's so beautiful
that it's beyond language.

389
00:23:12,320 --> 00:23:16,860
He doesn't have the language to
describe this world that he's in.

390
00:23:16,960 --> 00:23:19,260
Okay? This is beyond
language. And finally,

391
00:23:19,840 --> 00:23:24,740
he develops the courage to

392
00:23:24,740 --> 00:23:27,400
stare up in the sky, and he sees the sun.

393
00:23:27,640 --> 00:23:28,900
Okay? The sun.

394
00:23:30,540 --> 00:23:32,520
And he is amazed.

395
00:23:32,520 --> 00:23:36,020
He is amazed by how the sun
is a source of all life.

396
00:23:36,200 --> 00:23:38,940
And now, for the first time,

397
00:23:39,020 --> 00:23:42,280
he fully understands
the truth of the world.

398
00:23:43,340 --> 00:23:45,760
Okay? And when he does,

399
00:23:46,240 --> 00:23:49,540
he is seized by regret, because

400
00:23:49,540 --> 00:23:52,540
he remembers he has all these friends

401
00:23:53,260 --> 00:23:57,580
who are still trapped and
in prison in the cave.

402
00:23:57,760 --> 00:24:00,900
And he pities them. So
he swears that he will.

403
00:24:01,480 --> 00:24:03,540
Even though he. He loves where he is.

404
00:24:03,680 --> 00:24:05,940
He will still venture back into the cave

405
00:24:05,940 --> 00:24:10,440
in order to show people
the truth of the world.

406
00:24:10,580 --> 00:24:14,500
And to tell them that you've
been living a lie all your life.

407
00:24:14,640 --> 00:24:16,720
Okay? So he goes back into the cave.

408
00:24:16,920 --> 00:24:20,760
Now remember, his eyes are
now accustomed to sunlight.

409
00:24:21,320 --> 00:24:22,940
So in the cave, it's all dark.

410
00:24:23,240 --> 00:24:25,120
So he stumbles around. He stumbles around.

411
00:24:25,220 --> 00:24:26,540
He falls. And he hurts himself.

412
00:24:26,760 --> 00:24:30,260
Okay? And then he goes
and talks to the prisoners

413
00:24:30,260 --> 00:24:31,920
and tells them, hey.

414
00:24:32,320 --> 00:24:34,040
I've been to the outside world.

415
00:24:34,320 --> 00:24:36,420
I've been to the sunlight.

416
00:24:36,580 --> 00:24:37,920
I know what truth is.

417
00:24:38,840 --> 00:24:43,080
And then they're like, can you
describe to us what it's like then?

418
00:24:43,900 --> 00:24:45,260
And he can't do it.

419
00:24:45,300 --> 00:24:49,680
Okay? And then they're like,
tell us what you see on the wall.

420
00:24:50,240 --> 00:24:52,280
And because he's been
so accustomed to truth,

421
00:24:52,400 --> 00:24:56,200
he can no longer use human
language to describe anything.

422
00:24:56,900 --> 00:25:01,540
Okay? Okay? And so the
people are convinced.

423
00:25:02,340 --> 00:25:04,060
Utterly convinced. He's an idiot.

424
00:25:04,200 --> 00:25:05,800
He's insane. He's a clown.

425
00:25:07,200 --> 00:25:10,760
And so they refuse to follow him.

426
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:12,820
And at some point, because

427
00:25:12,820 --> 00:25:17,320
he insists on revealing the truth to them,

428
00:25:17,400 --> 00:25:19,860
they kill him. Okay?

429
00:25:20,440 --> 00:25:21,980
That's the allegory of the cave.

430
00:25:22,140 --> 00:25:25,080
Okay? And you'll remember this
allegory for the rest of your life.

431
00:25:25,620 --> 00:25:29,200
Now this allegory is
powerful for three reasons.

432
00:25:29,340 --> 00:25:31,440
Okay? Okay? And I want you to
remember these three reasons.

433
00:25:31,440 --> 00:25:34,720
Because we will go into them
later on in the course.

434
00:25:34,880 --> 00:25:37,900
The first reason is, who's the man

435
00:25:37,900 --> 00:25:41,020
who goes out in the
sunlight and sees the truth?

436
00:25:41,200 --> 00:25:42,420
It's obviously Socrates.

437
00:25:42,640 --> 00:25:46,060
Right? So with this allegory,

438
00:25:46,120 --> 00:25:50,140
Plato redeems the reputation of Socrates.

439
00:25:50,280 --> 00:25:54,840
Right? Because remember,
before, Socrates was despised.

440
00:25:54,860 --> 00:25:56,640
He was laughed at by the Athenians.

441
00:25:57,300 --> 00:26:01,420
And what this allegory is saying is,
that's because Socrates is a man.

442
00:26:01,420 --> 00:26:04,840
Socrates is a philosopher of the truth.

443
00:26:05,340 --> 00:26:08,120
Okay? And people cannot
deal with the truth.

444
00:26:09,040 --> 00:26:14,320
So that's why today we celebrate
Socrates as the greatest philosopher

445
00:26:14,320 --> 00:26:17,820
who ever lived. Not only that, but we
consider him the first philosopher,

446
00:26:17,940 --> 00:26:19,680
even though he was not
the first philosopher.

447
00:26:19,800 --> 00:26:21,440
Okay? Right?

448
00:26:21,500 --> 00:26:23,860
So that's the power of
the allegory of the cave.

449
00:26:23,940 --> 00:26:28,180
This image forever transforms
the way humanity understands

450
00:26:28,180 --> 00:26:30,140
and perceives Socrates.

451
00:26:30,440 --> 00:26:32,960
That's the first thing. Second thing is,

452
00:26:33,080 --> 00:26:35,120
this allegory becomes so powerful

453
00:26:35,120 --> 00:26:37,320
that

454
00:26:37,320 --> 00:26:41,360
in the imagination of Christians,

455
00:26:41,980 --> 00:26:44,400
Socrates becomes Jesus.

456
00:26:44,640 --> 00:26:49,380
Right? Does that make sense?

457
00:26:51,260 --> 00:26:53,120
Socrates is Jesus for Christians.

458
00:26:53,260 --> 00:26:55,880
Because Jesus was God, and

459
00:26:55,880 --> 00:27:00,020
he came down to our world
in order to speak the truth.

460
00:27:00,700 --> 00:27:05,180
And... Because we feared
the truth, we killed him.

461
00:27:06,500 --> 00:27:10,840
Okay? So, for Christians,

462
00:27:11,220 --> 00:27:16,100
allegory of the cave is really
the story of Jesus as well.

463
00:27:16,140 --> 00:27:18,980
Another martyr for the truth.

464
00:27:19,460 --> 00:27:21,680
But, and the last thing is,

465
00:27:21,880 --> 00:27:26,840
this allegory of the cave becomes
the framework for Christianity.

466
00:27:27,860 --> 00:27:31,320
Okay? Okay? It becomes the
intellectual framework for the...

467
00:27:31,420 --> 00:27:35,280
Religion of Christianity.
So let me show you how.

468
00:27:35,500 --> 00:27:38,200
Okay? So, this is an allegory.

469
00:27:38,320 --> 00:27:40,580
And behind the allegory,

470
00:27:40,620 --> 00:27:45,320
there is an understanding of
reality, a philosophy, a religion.

471
00:27:45,440 --> 00:27:48,500
Okay? So here is the platonic
understanding of the world.

472
00:27:49,300 --> 00:27:53,500
There's something called
the form of the good.

473
00:27:55,000 --> 00:27:59,200
Okay? And the, obviously the
metaphor would be the sun.

474
00:27:59,320 --> 00:28:01,400
Okay? And the form of the good is the sun.

475
00:28:01,400 --> 00:28:03,440
It's a source of everything.

476
00:28:04,060 --> 00:28:06,080
Okay? It's a source of all truth.

477
00:28:06,180 --> 00:28:08,720
It is the truth. It's
called the form of the good.

478
00:28:09,960 --> 00:28:13,260
And emanating from the form
of the good are concepts

479
00:28:13,260 --> 00:28:16,720
and ideals that structure the universe.

480
00:28:16,820 --> 00:28:19,380
And they are reason,

481
00:28:19,620 --> 00:28:23,740
beauty, and

482
00:28:23,740 --> 00:28:25,000
truth.

483
00:28:25,920 --> 00:28:27,180
And justice. Okay?

484
00:28:27,240 --> 00:28:29,380
And there are others. Okay?
But these are the main ones.

485
00:28:29,540 --> 00:28:31,060
Reason, truth, beauty, and justice.

486
00:28:31,400 --> 00:28:34,520
